\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {subsection}{\numberline {6.3}Planning Cost Analysis and Flat Failure}{10}{subsection.6.3}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{sec:planning_cost}{{6.3}{10}{Planning Cost Analysis and Flat Failure}{subsection.6.3}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{Vanishing value gradient.}{10}{section*.15}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{Hierarchical multi-scale gradients.}{10}{section*.16}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Planning cost comparison for UMaze.} (a) On the worst-case start--goal pair (maximum corridor distance), the hierarchical agent reaches the goal in 4 planning decisions (3 macro room-to-room transitions + 1 micro fine-tuning phase), while the flat agent exhausts all 5000 physics steps without reaching the goal due to vanishing value gradients. (b) Replanning cost when the goal changes: $k^2 = 16$ MACs for recomputing $\mathbf  {V}_{\text  {macro}}$ versus $N_v^2 \approx 12{,}544$ MACs for recomputing $\mathbf  {V}$---a $784\times $ reduction.}}{11}{figure.caption.17}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:umaze_planning}{{4}{11}{\textbf {Planning cost comparison for UMaze.} (a) On the worst-case start--goal pair (maximum corridor distance), the hierarchical agent reaches the goal in 4 planning decisions (3 macro room-to-room transitions + 1 micro fine-tuning phase), while the flat agent exhausts all 5000 physics steps without reaching the goal due to vanishing value gradients. (b) Replanning cost when the goal changes: $k^2 = 16$ MACs for recomputing $\Vmacro $ versus $N_v^2 \approx 12{,}544$ MACs for recomputing $\V $---a $784\times $ reduction}{figure.caption.17}{}}
